			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I should note there's also a &quot;newer&quot; way to to this (Windows 7 and up only; older Windows releases need to use the methodology already described) through <a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/aa373170(v=vs.85).aspx" class="postlink">Windows' Power Management API</a>.  Specifically I'm referring to <a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/dd405533(v=vs.85).aspx" class="postlink"><tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">PowerCreateRequest&#40;&#41;</tt></a> and <a href="https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/dd405534(v=vs.85).aspx" class="postlink"><tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">PowerSetRequest&#40;&#41;</tt></a> for the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">PowerRequestDisplayRequired</tt> <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">RequestType</tt>.<br /><br />The reason I mention this is that use of this API to inhibit display blanking/power-down/sleep allows a user to do <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">powercfg.exe -requests</tt> from the CLI and see which applications and/or drivers are inhibiting said condition.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

